Suddenly roses are putrid,

18:38.834 --> 18:41.066
and freshly baked bread,

18:41.133 --> 18:43.800
jeez, it's more like ammonia.

18:43.867 --> 18:45.867
Epileptics got
something similar.

18:45.934 --> 18:49.233
They can often tell when
they're about to do a back flip,

18:49.300 --> 18:52.133
because they start to smell
things that aren't there,

18:52.200 --> 18:54.400
so at least they got
a chance to sit down

18:54.467 --> 18:56.033
before the seizure hits.

18:56.100 --> 18:58.734
With pregnancy
and epilepsy,

18:58.800 --> 19:03.133
you've got a pretty good
sense of impending doom.

19:03.200 --> 19:06.467
Too bad we've got no sense
of how to avoid it.

19:12.133 --> 19:14.700
- I'm here
to work, Stella.

19:14.767 --> 19:15.934
- Hi, Robert.

19:16.000 --> 19:17.600
Give me a hand?

19:18.567 --> 19:22.066
I need you to take
the book cart around today.

19:24.233 --> 19:26.300
- William Blake.
- That's right.

19:26.367 --> 19:27.834
It's the cover to...

19:27.900 --> 19:30.000
"Songs of Experience."

19:31.867 --> 19:34.700
- I never expected to find
a Blake fan in here.

19:34.767 --> 19:38.266
- I'm sorry, I have to ask,
why are you here?

19:38.333 --> 19:42.367
Why would you work in Oz
as opposed to some city library

19:42.433 --> 19:44.967
where you wouldn't be surprised
to find a Blake fan?

19:45.033 --> 19:49.433
- Well, one day
about a year ago,

19:49.500 --> 19:52.600
I was home taking a shower
and I heard a noise.

19:52.667 --> 19:54.300
I came out of
the bathroom,

19:54.367 --> 19:56.400
and there was this kid
standing in the hallway

19:56.467 --> 19:59.533
with my DVD player.

20:00.700 --> 20:03.834
There I am,
"au natural,"

20:03.900 --> 20:07.400
and though I consider
my body a beautiful sight,

20:07.467 --> 20:09.734
the kid freaks
and jumps out the window.

20:09.800 --> 20:11.300
He twists his ankle.

20:11.367 --> 20:14.000
A couple of minutes later
the police pick him up.

20:14.066 --> 20:15.934
It seems he's robbed
other people as well.

20:16.000 --> 20:21.367
So, I go downtown to testify
at some pretrial thing,

20:21.433 --> 20:26.266
and there's the kid,
Jermaine.

20:26.333 --> 20:29.567
So small, so sweet,
sitting next to his mother.

20:29.633 --> 20:32.066
I think,
"He's going to jail."

20:32.133 --> 20:36.700
Then I think, "Christ,
he can have my DVD player."

20:36.767 --> 20:38.567
- You could have
dropped the charges.

20:38.633 --> 20:41.066
- I did, but everyone else
held firm.

20:41.133 --> 20:44.667
I went and visited Jermaine
at juvenile detention

20:44.734 --> 20:46.600
and I said to him,
"Why aren't you in school?"

20:46.667 --> 20:48.200
And you know
what he told me?

20:48.266 --> 20:49.433
- He couldn't read.

20:49.500 --> 20:52.367
- It broke my heart.

20:53.633 --> 21:00.133
I went to Plymouth House
every week and taught him,

21:00.200 --> 21:03.900
and he took to words
like a plant to rain.

21:03.967 --> 21:08.033
His mind was so sharp,
so alive, so thirsty.

21:08.100 --> 21:09.700
- That's wonderful.

21:09.767 --> 21:12.033
- He got stabbed
and died.

21:15.834 --> 21:17.433
And even though
I knew there were

21:17.500 --> 21:18.967
others like him
in Plymouth,

21:19.033 --> 21:20.700
I couldn't go back.

21:21.934 --> 21:25.600
I also know I couldn't
stop what I'd started.

21:25.667 --> 21:28.200
So...

21:28.266 --> 21:29.934
Ta-da.

21:30.000 --> 21:31.100
- You came to a place filled

21:31.166 --> 21:32.734
with old books and bad
attitudes.

21:32.800 --> 21:35.266
- The truth is, Robert,

21:35.333 --> 21:37.166
